From: ETK GTK Edition <mercurious>
Subject: [PATCH v0.7.3] KERS stage 1, semapark-v2 — park the FLIP semaphore too
 (cumulative; supersedes semapark-v1)

v1's on-rig counters delivered the verdict in one afternoon: during normal
racing the non-flip wait path is nearly silent (sq~0 over whole sessions),
while the FLIP semaphore — the one wait v1 excluded for safety — is where
the machine burns: one NPEA00502 perfstat interval logged sw=5,554,102 with
pk=0 (a ~13-16M laps/s monitor-clear hot spin; ~8.4B laps over one 821 s
session ~= the rsx thread spending most of the session spinning on the flip
label), and semaphore_acquire held at 10.3-11.5% of all process cycles.
Where a non-flip wait WAS eligible, the park worked at 89% efficiency
(sw=4983 -> pk=4451, the 00E59485 wedge interval).

Change vs v1: the flip semaphore parks under its own tighter bound
GTK_SEMA_PARK_FLIP_US (default 100 us — <=0.6% of a 16.7 ms frame in added
flip-detection latency) with its own kill-switch GTK_SEMA_PARK_FLIP=0
(restores the v1 exclusion; GTK_SEMA_PARK=0 still kills everything). New
perfstat field pf= counts flip parks separately from pk=. During a real
00E5 wedge the flip label never signals — the anti-lock nets own recovery;
parking merely stops the doomed wait from cooking a core while they work.
Self-IDs "GTK Edition v0.7.3".

Base: v0.0.41-19544-60c9705a + 0.7.0 patch set + perfstat-v1. Cumulative:
includes all of semapark-v1 (spin->park escalation, sq/sw/pk counters).
Design + evidence: ETK dossier KersConcept_20260712.md (K1, v2 addendum).

